ickid">Samsung S95B</a> has a QD-OLED display that combines an OLED panel with a layer of quantum dots. This allows it to display the high contrast and deep blacks of any good OLED TV without sacrificing as much in the way of peak brightness or color saturation. It should deliver consistently smooth motion, and it has four HDMI 2.1 ports that can play up to 4K 120Hz. It also supports ALLM, all the major VRR formats and HDR10 and HDR10+.</p><p> However, the S95B doesn&#39;t work with Dolby Vision HDR, and it&#39;s only available in 55- and 65-inch sizes. Beyond that, <a data-i13n="cpos:29;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsImxhbmRpbmdVcmwiOiJodHRwczovL3VzLmNvbW11bml0eS5zYW1zdW5nLmNvbS90NS80Sy04Sy1hbmQtT3RoZXItVFZzL1M5NUItMTQyMC05LWlzc3Vlcy10aGF0LW5lZWQtYWRkcmVzc2luZy90ZC1wLzI0NzI4NzUiLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6ImY1ODQzYTUwLTFjMTEtNDllZS1iZjg2LTJmYTVkNDIxOTQ0MCJ9&amp;signature=AQAAAafHz4s4nRyeVXnYHLDCJQXtzJOWSib0AODXfNzD0T1e&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fus.community.samsung.com%2Ft5%2F4K-8K-and-Other-TVs%2FS95B-1420-9-issues-that-need-addressing%2Ftd-p%2F2472875&amp;uuid=uVa2X4QR24wswN1830983">some S95B</a> <a data-i13n="cpos:30;pos:1" href="https://www.rtings.com/tv/discussions/I6IKUBFqpNRVtr9O/gamers-beware-of-1420-update-game-mode-hdr-hgig-dim">owners</a> have complained about issues with the TV&#39;s picture quality while in “Game Mode” after firmware updates. This shouldn&#39;t make the S95B anywhere close to a poor TV, and it can still be worth it if you play in a bright room. But we&#39;re a little more hesitant to recommend it over the LG C2 for gaming specifically.</p><p> If it falls into the S95B&#39;s price range, the new <a data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Samsung Electronics;elmt:;cpos:31;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=f85e63cd-e13c-4f9d-991c-9fbaadede3ac&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Samsung+Electronics&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAczf842mSY9bvjZ_ZCfLTUmnTeMe1-a9gU0M8LmSEol7&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.samsung.com%2Fus%2Ftelevisions-home-theater%2Ftvs%2Foled-tvs%2F55-class-s90c-oled-4k-smart-tv-2023-qn55s90cafxza%2F" class="rapid-with-clickid">Samsung S90C</a> should be a better buy than its predecessor. Its panel appears to be extremely similar to the S95B, but it adds ( <a data-i13n="cpos:32;pos:1" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5A8GUUuF0Gw">official</a> ) 4K 144Hz support, which is nice if you ever want to hook up a gaming PC. It&#39;s also available in 77- and 83-inch sizes. It costs a few hundred dollars more than the S95B as of this writing, though. For most people, the differences don&#39;t appear to be stark enough to warrant the upgrade.</p><p> This year&#39;s <a data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;cpos:33;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9ncC9wcm9kdWN0L0IwQldGU0ZEN1A_dGFnPWdkZ3QwYy1wLW8tcDAtMjAiLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6ImY1ODQzYTUwLTFjMTEtNDllZS1iZjg2LTJmYTVkNDIxOTQ0MCJ9&amp;signature=AQAAAYTeyGMS_1upG09UvYcDp6W5tt5gGTUBWGIeLgOfZriG&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fgp%2Fproduct%2FB0BWFSFD7P" class="rapid-with-clickid">Samsung S95C</a> , meanwhile, is the actual follow-up to the S95B. It, too, can play in 4K at 144Hz, and some <a data-i13n="cpos:34;pos:1" href="https://www.rtings.com/tv/reviews/samsung/s95c-oled">reviews</a> <a data-i13n="cpos:35;pos:1" href="https://reviewed.usatoday.com/televisions/features/samsung-s95b-vs-samsung-s95c-which-should-you-buy">say</a> it can get a bit brighter than either the S95B or S90C in HDR. Since it runs its ports through an external box, the actual TV hardware is thinner, plus it&#39;s available in 77 inches on top of the usual 55- and 65-inch size options. It&#39;s even pricier than the S90C right now, however, so it&#39;s harder to justify unless money is no object.</p><h2> Sony A95K OLED </h2><p><core-commerce id="eb89fed88e1646c2bd89d0a5b9635c3f" data-type="product-list"></core-commerce></p><p> <a data-i13n="cpos:36;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9kcC9CMDlSOTVZUDM2P3RhZz1nZGd0MGMtcC1vLXAwLTIwIiwiY29udGVudFV1aWQiOiJmNTg0M2E1MC0xYzExLTQ5ZWUtYmY4Ni0yZmE1ZDQyMTk0NDAifQ&amp;signature=AQAAAVozk9MqJ1reWB6bmfRnwcOHeOy0JQuyg-UoSATj9OyE&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fdp%2FB09R95YP36&amp;uuid=eNmHi8BWCZ4q2oVl35983">Sony&#39;s A95K</a> is another well-regarded QD-OLED TV that <em>does</em> support Dolby Vision. It doesn&#39;t work with HDR10+, though, and it only has two full HDMI 2.1 ports. It&#39;s typically priced much higher than the C2 or S95B as well. The <a data-i13n="cpos:37;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/sony-2023-bravia-xr-tv-hands-on-bigger-brighter-and-even-better-looking-150030819.html">upcoming A95L</a> is worth monitoring, as it&#39;ll be one of the first TVs to support Dolby Vision at 4K 120Hz.</p><h2> Samsung QN90B </h2><p><core-commerce id="6d90fd701bdc4a32a67da33ab8a09319" data-type="product-list"></core-commerce></p><p> If you&#39;d prefer the extra brightness of a LCD TV, or if you think you might play one game (extremely) long enough to worry about <a data-i13n="cpos:38;pos:1" href="https://www.cnet.com/tech/home-entertainment/oled-screen-burn-in-rare-could-still-ruin-tv-nintendo-switch/">burn-in</a> , consider <a data-i13n="cpos:39;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Samsung Electronics;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=f85e63cd-e13c-4f9d-991c-9fbaadede3ac&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Samsung+Electronics&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAARGnOnQ1vSlqvY41-tZeI-nyN5TbicjjYfC0HZtAn8Rz&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.samsung.com%2Fus%2Ftelevisions-home-theater%2Ftvs%2Fsamsung-neo-qled-4k%2F55-class-qn90b-samsung-neo-qled-4k-smart-tv-2022-qn55qn90bafxza%2F">Samsung&#39;s QN90B</a> . It can&#39;t match the contrast, response time or viewing angles of a good OLED TV, but its Mini LED backlighting and quantum dot color should make for richer image quality than most LCD TVs, particularly in HDR. Its motion and input lag shouldn&#39;t cause problems, either, and it can get much brighter than the models above. Like other Samsung TVs, it doesn&#39;t support Dolby Vision, but it has four full HDMI 2.1 ports, ALLM and all the major VRR formats. It also comes in several screen sizes, with the <a data-i13n="cpos:40;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Samsung Electronics;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=f85e63cd-e13c-4f9d-991c-9fbaadede3ac&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Samsung+Electronics&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAbA_68DTN3i0YsTFoGpFALlVjhPwcCJ4iyHwcDwVCE49&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.samsung.com%2Fus%2Ftelevisions-home-theater%2Ftvs%2Fsamsung-neo-qled-4k%2F43-class-qn90b-samsung-neo-qled-4k-smart-tv-2022-qn43qn90bafxza%2F">43-</a> and <a data-i13n="cpos:41;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Samsung Electronics;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=f85e63cd-e13c-4f9d-991c-9fbaadede3ac&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Samsung+Electronics&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAZ_ZLgXJ5k8CIzSkD-oY2AmVjTq9LFyq4e5XMCC54Dcs&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.samsung.com%2Fus%2Ftelevisions-home-theater%2Ftvs%2Fsamsung-neo-qled-4k%2F50-class-qn90b-samsung-neo-qled-4k-smart-tv-2022-qn50qn90bafxza%2F">50-inch</a> models capable of hitting a 144Hz refresh rate. The rest go up to 120Hz, which is the max for a PS5 or Xbox Series X/S.</p><p> If the QN90B becomes unavailable by the time you read this, the newer <a data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;cpos:42;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9kcC9CMEJUVFZMNDE5P3RhZz1nZGd0MGMtcC1vLXAwLTIwIiwiY29udGVudFV1aWQiOiJmNTg0M2E1MC0xYzExLTQ5ZWUtYmY4Ni0yZmE1ZDQyMTk0NDAifQ&amp;signature=AQAAAcRaTCZXmi4ZFgpHBdxSGn_HdntJXBHTBv7CO897z6IG&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fdp%2FB0BTTVL419" class="rapid-with-clickid">Samsung QN90C</a> looks to be another incremental upgrade that should offer similar performance. In either case, note that the 43- and 50-inch versions of these TVs also use VA panels, which should result in better contrast but worse viewing angles.</p><h2> Hisense U8H </h2><p><core-commerce id="8144f7ea0b3f4ded9c9b762298460fdb" data-type="product-list"></core-commerce></p><p> Those Samsung TVs aren&#39;t cheap, though. For those on a tighter budget, the <a data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;cpos:43;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9kcC9CMEI1WVpOWlRaP3RhZz1nZGd0MGMtcC1vLXAwLTIwIiwiY29udGVudFV1aWQiOiJmNTg0M2E1MC0xYzExLTQ5ZWUtYmY4Ni0yZmE1ZDQyMTk0NDAifQ&amp;signature=AQAAAddl9oD3IDpv38BSp8QBTDUrI8Q0HwinOpQL7IHwY-vA&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fdp%2FB0B5YZNZTZ" class="rapid-with-clickid">Hisense U8H</a> should work fine. It&#39;s a step down from the QN90B, as it has worse viewing angles and only two full HDMI 2.1 ports, but it should still look good in any environment, with low input lag, good brightness, support for all the main HDR and VRR technologies, and 4K 120Hz support. Motion won&#39;t look quite as smooth as it would on a good OLED TV, however.</p><p> The 2023 version of this TV, the <a data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;cpos:44;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9IaXNlbnNlLTU1LUluY2gtQ2xhc3MtTWluaS1MRUQtR29vZ2xlL2RwL0IwQzczSDhQVlQ_dGFnPWdkZ3QwYy1wLW8tcDAtMjAiLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6ImY1ODQzYTUwLTFjMTEtNDllZS1iZjg2LTJmYTVkNDIxOTQ0MCJ9&amp;signature=AQAAAZopYOthgg5x5l5Hcxhrz-Lw221lfCxoxRXzteQfLSsJ&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FHisense-55-Inch-Class-Mini-LED-Google%2Fdp%2FB0C73H8PVT" class="rapid-with-clickid">Hisense U8K</a> , promises a faster 144Hz refresh rate and more full-array local dimming zones to help with contrast. Reviews are still scarce as of this writing, but if you see it for around the same price as the U8H, it <em>should</em> be an upgrade.</p><p> We&#39;ve previously highlighted <a data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;cpos:45;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9ncC9wcm9kdWN0L0IwQjdaWEdDVlk_dGFnPWdkZ3QwYy1wLW8tcDAtMjAiLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6ImY1ODQzYTUwLTFjMTEtNDllZS1iZjg2LTJmYTVkNDIxOTQ0MCJ9&amp;signature=AQAAAc3vlyi6-ptVq6AyWc4dEFi200ohBfYqQKTaOZbCDEU1&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fgp%2Fproduct%2FB0B7ZXGCVY" class="rapid-with-clickid">TCL&#39;s 6-Series (R655) TV</a> in this spot. That one also supports 4K at 144Hz, but it appears to be fully out of stock, and <a data-i13n="cpos:46;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/tcls-new-2023-tvs-deliver-high-frame-rate-gaming-at-lower-prices-165458947.html">TCL&#39;s 2023 TV lineup</a> doesn&#39;t have a true like-for-like replacement with Mini LED backlighting in the same price range.</p><h2> Vizio M-Series Quantum X </h2><p><core-commerce id="a0d2ae1992e7418c8ff8cf81acfd3940" data-type="product-list"></core-commerce></p><p> <a data-i13n="cpos:47;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9kcC9CMDlWQ1pDUjFXP3RoPTEmdGFnPWdkZ3QwYy1wLW8tcDAtMjAiLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6ImY1ODQzYTUwLTFjMTEtNDllZS1iZjg2LTJmYTVkNDIxOTQ0MCJ9&amp;signature=AQAAAZG1xD_8JObOoYjYN7U9Tpj7xW3-nWdFo1u_OSHAG-OX&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fdp%2FB09VCZCR1W%3Fth%3D1">Vizio&#39;s M-Series Quantum X</a> doesn&#39;t look as nice as some of our other picks, but for frame rate junkies it supports a 120Hz refresh rate, with its 50-inch model capable of reaching 240Hz, albeit at a 1080p resolution. For PC gamers who want to dabble in competitive shooters like <em>Counter-Strike</em> , it&#39;s an outlier for a big display in this price range.</p><h2> TCL 5-Series </h2><p><core-commerce id="155852d5cbaf41daaa5c448ba4d9be08" data-type="product-list"></core-commerce></p><p> On the lower end, <a data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;cpos:48;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9UQ0wtQ2xhc3MtRG9sYnktVmlzaW9uLUZyZWVTeW5jL2RwL0IwQjgxRFZRTks_dGFnPWdkZ3QwYy1wLW8tcDAtMjAiLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6ImY1ODQzYTUwLTFjMTEtNDllZS1iZjg2LTJmYTVkNDIxOTQ0MCJ9&amp;signature=AQAAAb2ghNl4HPWgQvVXpipUgAbG_Hq-JRI-Udg7QaSPUdU8&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FTCL-Class-Dolby-Vision-FreeSync%2Fdp%2FB0B81DVQNK" class="rapid-with-clickid">TCL&#39;s 5-Series (S555)</a> is a highly-rated QLED TV with low lag, HDR, local dimming and solid contrast for the money. It technically supports VRR, too, but like many cheaper TVs, it&#39;s limited to a 60Hz refresh rate and lacks HDMI 2.1.</p><p> This is another 2022 TV that looks to be flickering out of stock, though. If you can afford to pay a little bit more (for now), the <a data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;cpos:49;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9IaXNlbnNlLTU1LUluY2gtQ2xhc3MtTWluaS1MRUQtR29vZ2xlL2RwL0IwQzZXTFdRNVI_dGFnPWdkZ3QwYy1wLW8tcDAtMjAiLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6ImY1ODQzYTUwLTFjMTEtNDllZS1iZjg2LTJmYTVkNDIxOTQ0MCJ9&amp;signature=AQAAAR2gN9a4gVg7XLTrzoE_S91lfZT2L4UJnb_h3I3QXXD6&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FHisense-55-Inch-Class-Mini-LED-Google%2Fdp%2FB0C6WLWQ5R" class="rapid-with-clickid">Hisense U6K</a> looks like a strong alternative for 2023. Like the 5-Series, it&#39;s stuck at 60Hz and doesn&#39;t include HDMI 2.1 ports, but it does have a Mini LED backlight, which is uncommon for a lower-budget TV. <a data-i13n="cpos:50;pos:1" href="https://reviewed.usatoday.com/televisions/content/hisense-u6k-mini-led-tv-review">Recent</a> <a data-i13n="cpos:51;pos:1" href="https://www.pcmag.com/reviews/hisense-65-inch-u6-series-uled-tv-65u6k">reviews</a> say it delivers better contrast and color volume than most options in this part of the market as a result. It technically supports the most prominent HDR standards as well.</p><p> <em>Richard Lawler contributed to this report.</em></p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/best-tvs-for-gaming-180033983.html?src=rss]]>;</description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/best-tvs-for-gaming-180033983.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> f5843a50-1c11-49ee-bf86-2fa5d4219440</guid><dc:creator> Jeff Dunn</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher>恩杰特</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder>恩杰特</dc:rightsholder><pubDate>Wed, 26 Jul 2023 13:15:09 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1690379587</ingested><modified> 2023-07-26T13:53:21+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Consumer Discretionary]]></category><category><![CDATA[Video Technology]]></category><category><![CDATA[Shopping]]></category><category><![CDATA[Technology & Electronics]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Jeff Dunn]]></category><media:content height="4584" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2021-02/eedba4b0-76cc-11eb-aff7-b3bb49e900d8" width="8149"><media:keywords>标题</media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="4584" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2021-02/eedba4b0-76cc-11eb-aff7-b3bb49e900d8" width="8149"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[Future Publishing via Getty Images]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[Living room with Microsoft Xbox Series X (L) and Sony PlayStation 5 home video game consoles alongside a television and soundbar, taken on November 3, 2020. (Photo by Phil Barker/Future Publishing via Getty Images)]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[Xbox Series X & PlayStation 5]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[Bumble spins its BFF friend-finding feature off into a standalone app]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p> Seven years after Bumble launched <a data-i13n="cpos:1;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/2016-03-04-bumble-now-lets-you-to-find-a-new-bff.html">Bumble BFF</a> , the company is finally giving users their own app for making friends. Bumble has announced the release of Bumble For Friends, an app dedicated solely to finding friends in your area. The company started testing the app earlier this year in the United Kingdom and select regions of Asia, <a data-i13n="cpos:2;pos:1" href="https://mashable.com/article/bumble-bff-standalone-app"><em>Mashable</em> reported</a> .</p><p> Bumble For Friends will function almost exactly like Bumble BFF (which makes up 15 percent of Bumble&#39;s monthly active users, a <a data-i13n="cpos:3;pos:1" href="https://techcrunch.com/2023/06/21/bumble-is-testing-a-separate-bff-app-for-finding-friends/">Bumble spokesperson told <em>TechCrunch</em></a> ). However, there will be no need to download a dating app — something coupled-up users will likely be happy about. Like a dating app, though, you create a profile with a mix of photos, information about yourself and responses to prompts. It can include things like if you drink, your political affiliation, your relationship status and why you&#39;re looking to make friends. Your Bumble For Friends profile will also have space to share some of your interests, like dogs or dancing — one of the things <a data-i13n="cpos:4;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/bumble-private-detection-open-source-192530832.html">Bumble</a> uses to help match you with potential friends.</p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><p> There is one new feature on Bumble For Friends: the option to create a group chat. Basically, if you think any of your matches would also get along, you can add two or more of them to a group chat. To use this option, go into the conversations tab and pick a Bumble-suggested activity or add your own. You can also just give the group chat a name (which you can edit later on) if you don&#39;t want to pick what to do. From there, you can invite matches and get talking. Invitees will receive a notification about the chat showing them your chosen title or the potential activity.</p><p> Bumble For Friends is free to download on Apple&#39;s App Store or the Google Play Store. You can create a new account or log into your existing one and have your profile and matches transferred over. At that point, your Bumble BFF account will disappear from the original app, but you can still use <a data-i13n="cpos:5;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/bumble-virtual-dating-coronavirus-165215408.html">Date</a> or <a data-i13n="cpos:6;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/2017-10-02-bizz-bumble-app-for-networking.html">Bizz</a> modes. Bumble doesn&#39;t seem to be forcing anyone to switch to the new app, so you can still keep all your accounts in one place if you prefer.</p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/bumble-spins-its-bff-friend-finding-feature-off-into-a-standalone-app-130040779.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/bumble-spins-its-bff-friend-finding-feature-off-into-a-standalone-app-130040779.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> eef9aad5-aafd-4fc2-acca-0b10c9c0e4d4</guid><dc:creator> Sarah Fielding</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher>恩杰特</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder>恩杰特</dc:rightsholder><pubDate>Wed, 26 Jul 2023 13:00:40 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1689937617</ingested><modified> 2023-07-21T11:07:03+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Software]]></category><category><![CDATA[Technology & Electronics]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Sarah Fielding]]></category><media:content height="810" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/67c76b30-27aa-11ee-be77-4c5a1d29525d" width="1200"><media:keywords>标题</media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="810" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/67c76b30-27aa-11ee-be77-4c5a1d29525d" width="1200"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[Bumble]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[Two profile photos show up with a star in between them and a phone saying "You're friends!"]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[Bumble for friends]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[The man behind the USB-C iPhone rebuilt the AirPods Pro case to make it repairable]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p> Robotics engineer Ken Pillonel, known for creating a makeshift <a data-i13n="cpos:1;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/the-usb-c-i-phone-becomes-a-reality-thanks-to-a-robotics-engineer-113556672.html">USB-C iPhone</a> and <a data-i13n="cpos:2;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/an-engineer-just-made-the-first-airpods-that-charge-with-usb-c-141540375.html">AirPods</a> , has revealed his next project. The modding wunderkind has deconstructed <a data-i13n="cpos:3;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/airpods-pro-review-second-generation-130048218.html">Apple&#39;s AirPods Pro</a> case and built a custom repairable version. Pillonel is sharing the design for free, allowing enterprising self-repair enthusiasts with a knack for engineering to make their own.</p><p> Pillonel has already tackled the AirPods Pro with a <a data-i13n="cpos:4;pos:1" href="https://www.engadget.com/a-robotics-engineer-is-trying-to-make-the-airpods-pro-easier-to-repair-184249580.html">custom replaceable printed circuit board (PCB)</a> . However, his new project attempts to dissect the earbuds&#39; entire case, offering a complete blueprint for others to do the same — with 3D-printed sections and a few (cheap) afterparty parts. “Most gadgets are designed without repairability in mind, unlike the durable technology of the past that seemed built to last,” Pillonel wrote, noting that <em>iFixit</em> gave the second-gen AirPods Pro a <a data-i13n="cpos:5;pos:1" href="https://www.ifixit.com/News/66194/apples-new-airpods-are-telling-users-to-replace-the-batteries-already-too-bad-thats-impossible">dismal zero repairability score</a> . “It is troubling to see design choices like non-replaceable batteries, glued-in components, and a lack of transparency in public information leading to the rise of &#39;fast electronics.&#39;”</p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><p> In response, the engineer took on this latest project “to demonstrate how one of the most popular gadgets today — Apple&#39;s AirPods Pro — could have been easily made repairable with minimal effort.” His stated goal is to inspire consumers and multi-billion-dollar corporations <em>(ahem, Apple)</em> to treat technology less like a locked-down disposable commodity and more like something one can tinker with, learn from and — with the right skills — repair themselves. Of course, a central component is using screws and nuts instead of adhesives to create a makeshift case you can crack open and fix down the road. </p><figure><img src="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/7e3d06a0-2b0a-11ee-9cf7-c6a13c62df3d" style="height:1200px;width:2000px;" alt="Engineer Ken Pillonel working with a 3D printer. He is to the right / front of the printer, looking inside of it." data-uuid="799bc85c-d05c-3116-a72f-61ae31de7a42"><figcaption></figcaption><div class="photo-credit"> Ken Pillonel / Exploring the Simulation</div></figure><p> Pillonel says this was one of his most challenging custom projects yet, as he had to create precise scans of the case&#39;s every component. As he explains in the video below from his <a data-i13n="cpos:6;pos:1" href="https://www.youtube.com/@ExploringTheSimulation">YouTube channel</a> , some of the case&#39;s parts proved especially difficult with complex curves that a simple caliper and basic 2D scans couldn&#39;t quite nail down. He even detailed his quest for finding the right spring-loaded contact pins to charge the buds and an affordable 3D scanner to capture some of the more oddly shaped parts. I recommend a quick watch to anyone curious about sustainability and the nuts and bolts behind iconic consumer tech gadgets. (Remember that such tinkering will void your warranty, and you should probably only give it a shot if you&#39;re experienced with electronics repairs.)</p><p> “I am thrilled to make these repairable designs available to the public at no cost, encouraging individuals and manufacturers alike to prioritize repairability in their product development,” Pillonel wrote today. “Together, we can work towards a circular economy that not only minimizes electronic waste but also fosters a culture of conscious consumption and responsible tech innovation.” You can peruse Pillonel&#39;s designs and storefront for replacement parts on <a data-i13n="cpos:7;pos:1" href="https://shop.kenp.io/">his website</a> . </p><div id="075698e99c6f40ae9cf69c74023da671"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/OWoetPBipcI" title="YouTube 视频播放器" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen=""></iframe></div><p></p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/the-man-behind-the-usb-c-iphone-rebuilt-the-airpods-pro-case-to-make-it-repairable-130008565.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/the-man-behind-the-usb-c-iphone-rebuilt-the-airpods-pro-case-to-make-it-repairable-130008565.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> e0b344db-d66a-49d5-b01c-a7fd2d6bddc9</guid><dc:creator> Will Shanklin</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher>恩杰特</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder>恩杰特</dc:rightsholder><pubDate>Wed, 26 Jul 2023 13:00:08 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1690305418</ingested><modified> 2023-07-25T17:17:03+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Information Technology]]></category><category><![CDATA[Technology & Electronics]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Will Shanklin]]></category><media:content height="1500" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/136b4ad0-2b0a-11ee-adeb-e69074b08c79" width="2000"><media:keywords>标题</media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="1500" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2023-07/136b4ad0-2b0a-11ee-adeb-e69074b08c79" width="2000"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[2]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[Ken Pillonel / Exploring the Simulation]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[A custom AirPods Pro case with screws. A screwdriver is unscrewing one of the two visible screws. A lone AirPods Pro bud sits on the dark surface behind it.]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[Custom AirPods Pro case]]></media:title></media:content></item><item><title><![CDATA[Samsung Galaxy Unpacked 2023: Z Fold 5, Z Flip 5, Watch 6, Tab S9 and more]]></title><description type="html"><![CDATA[<p> Samsung has finally announced its next generation of foldable smartphones, and a whole lot more. The company hosted its first ever Galaxy Unpacked event from its hometown of Seoul, South Korea overnight, and, in addition to the Z Fold 5 and Z Flip 5, we also saw a new Galaxy Watch and Galaxy Tab Ultra. </p><div id="e8e8a0df50b949df846983165c8c51ae"><div style="left:0;width:100%;height:0;position:relative;padding-bottom:56.25%;"><iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/MlJclQRdL2M?rel=0" style="top:0;left:0;width:100%;height:100%;position:absolute;border:0;" allowfullscreen="" scrolling="no"></iframe></div></div><p><br> Engadget&#39;s Richard Lai was on the ground in South Korea, supported by Mat Smith from a satellite event in London, England. The show&#39;s over now, but you can relive their liveblog here, or check out our first hands-on previews and comparison posts below.</p><span id="end-legacy-contents"></span><h2> Samsung Galaxy Unpacked July 2023 in-depth coverage</h2><ul><li>